The complete genome sequences of several pairs of closely related prokaryotes are now available. Surprisingly, even strains of the same species can differ by as much as 20 % in gene content. Several analyses of very closely related genomes comparisons reported over the last years show that there may be as much to learn about diversity. Extensive genomic comparisons are possible not only between representatives of distant evolutionary phyla, but also between species of the same phylogenetic branch where individual evolutionary events can be more readily identified. They also indicate that sequencing of one representative genome give us nowhere near a complete picture of the genetic repertoire of any species, and that new and comparative methods will be required. Remarkable innovation in sequencing technologies has been achieved making them high-throughput, faster and more cost effective. The sequencing field has experienced a major shift by the introduction of innovation sequencing technologies capable of generating sequence data at a fraction of the cost and much quicker when compared to the Sanger method. Bacteria are characterized by extensive intraspecies variation. There is not only the sequence variation found in all species, but also the presence or absence of whole genes or clusters of genes. We propose to apply the sequencing technology developed by Illumina on several strains of Lactobacillus acidophilus and helveticus to enable a comparative study that will link genotype and phenotype at the genomic level.

Hop tolerance is a prerequisite for beer spoilage bacteria. Lactobacillus brevis is the major spoiler in beer, affecting beer quality and causing economic losses in breweries. Although several hop resistant genes have been identified, controversies still exist about the number of, and role of, genes associated with growth in beer. In this study, 21 L.brevis were screened for hop tolerance and three hop tolerant as well as two hop-acid sensitive strains were selected for further investigation. Furthermore, one tolerant strain was plasmid-cured rendering it sensitive as determined by growth experiments. Whole genome sequencing of the five strains and the plasmid-cured strain was performed and followed by in-depth comparative genomics analysis between the tested strains as well as between the tested strains and previously published L.brevis genomes. The physiological differences between the tolerant wildtype and the sensitive variant allowed for the identification of chromosome- and plasmid-borne features, which contribute to hop tolerance. In addition, several new genes associated with growth in hop containing media were detected by the genomic comparison of tolerant versus sensitive strains. These genes could serve as additional marker genes to detect very potent spoilage bacteria in breweries. Our findings underline the notion that the ability to grow in beer, which is a hostile environment (low pH, hop-acid, ethanol), is a multi-factorial property, and therefore requires a combination of several marker genes and techniques like multiplex-PCR to predict the spoilage potential of L.brevis in breweries.

Lactobacillus brevis is a kind of food spoilage bacteria which have the ability to enter into VBNC state. Due to the VBNC state, Lactobacillus brevis can evade the microbiological detecting of food and result in the food spoilage during the expiration date which effect the food safety and the whole food industry. Thorough understanding of the genome of Lactobacillus brevis is required to pick out the genes related to the VBNC state and aid in the further study of the control of Lactobacillus brevis.

Isolation Source: Brassica oleracea var. capitata cultivar Varazdinski
Isolation Comments: isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B
Comments: The research in the frame of Croatian Science Foundation project entitled „Probiotics and starter cultures – surface proteins and bacteriocins“ is aimed to deliver new generation of probiotics and functional starter cultures, thoughtfully characterised and with specific features such as production of functional surface (S)-layer proteins and bacteriocins with broad spectrum of activity towards potential food contaminants and pathogens. Among more than 200 different LAB strains isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B. Importance of S-layer proteins lies in increasing scientific evidences that some probiotic properties of lactic acid bacteria (LAB), such as enhanced survival in rigorous conditions in gastrointestinal tract and during the process of freeze-drying, adhesion to intestinal epithelial cells or inhibition of pathogens, are related to the occurrence of those proteins. Hence, it is believed that the production of S-layer proteins might be a selective criterion indicating probiotic effect of Lactobacillus species that express those specific surface proteins. Another feature specific to certain strains of LAB, which gives them a selective advantage when applied as probiotic or starter cultures, is the production of bacteriocins. Among all the isolated autochthonous LAB, three Lactobaillus plantarum strains, M92C, SF15C and D13, showed advanced bacteriocinogenic potential. Besides their application as probiotics, these strains could be considered as starter cultures with potential to improve the functionality and quality of various fermented products, while in the same time preserving their traditional sensory characteristics.

Sequencing Centers: University of Wisconsin-Madison and Utah State University
Isolation Comments: isolated from dairy, plant, and human sources
Comments: The broad ecological adaptability of Lactobacillus casei facilitates widespread application of this organism in the food and health industries.  To identify the genomic features of L. casei that contribute to evolution and lifestyle adaptation of the species, we performed comparative genomic analysis of 17 L. casei genomes representing strains isolated from dairy, plant, and human sources.  Gene gain, via acquisition of genomic islands, likely confers a fitness benefit in specific habitats.  The loss of unnecessary ancestral traits was especially pronounced in strains that show specialization for a cheese environment, where gene decay likely results in enhanced fitness in the dairy niche.  This study gives the first picture of the L. casei pangenome and provides valuable insights into evolution and lifestyle adaptation of this important bacterium.

Comments: The broad ecological adaptability of Lactobacillus casei facilitates widespread application of this organism in the food and health industries.  To identify the genomic features of L. casei that contribute to evolution and lifestyle adaptation of the species, we performed comparative genomic analysis of 17 L. casei genomes representing strains isolated from dairy, plant, and human sources.  Gene gain, via acquisition of genomic islands, likely confers a fitness benefit in specific habitats.  The loss of unnecessary ancestral traits was especially pronounced in strains that show specialization for a cheese environment, where gene decay likely results in enhanced fitness in the dairy niche.  This study gives the first picture of the L. casei pangenome and provides valuable insights into evolution and lifestyle adaptation of this important bacterium.

Isolation Comments: isolated from the human upper respiratory tract
Comments: Although the genotypic and phenotypic properties of the Lactobacillus casei group have been studied extensively, the taxonomic structure has been the subject of debate for a long time. Here, we performed a large-scale comparative analysis using 183 publicly available genomes, supplemented with a Lactobacillus strain isolated from the human upper respiratory tract. Based on this analysis we identified inconsistencies in the taxonomy and reclassified all genomes according to their most closely related type strain. This led to the identification of a catalase-encoding gene in all ten L. casei sensu stricto strains making it the first described catalase-positive species in the Lactobacillus genus. Moreover, we found that six out of ten L. casei genomes contained a SecA2/SecY2 gene cluster with two putative glycosylated surface adhesin proteins. Altogether, our results highlight current inconsistencies in the taxonomy of the L. casei group and reveals new clade-associated functional features.

The Project is focused on the study, understanding and exploitation of aerobic and respiratory metabolism in wild and mutant strains of Lactobacillus casei group. In particular, the effect of aerobic and respiratory metabolism on the growth, stress tolerance, proteomic and metabolic profiles has been investigated in different strains of L. casei group, in order to improve survival of starter and probiotic cultures and to enhance the nutritional and technological properties of fermented foods. A complex approach based on transcriptomic, proteomic and metabolomic analyses has been used to carry out all research activities.

Comments: Recently, bacterial communities (microbiota) have been discovered in the female bladder. Thus, the “sterile urine” paradigm is no longer valid. We have begun to sequence and annotate the genomes of these isolated bacteria.

Isolation Comments: isolated in Bulgaria in 1969 from home-made yoghurt
Comments: Lactobacillus delbrueckii ssp. bulgaricus strain LBB.B5 was isolated in Bulgaria in 1969 from home-made yoghurt. The strain was chosen for industrial application for yoghurt starters for its ability to form a strong association with selected Streptococcus thermophilus strains. The extent of protocooperation occurring between L. delbrueckii ssp. bulgaricus LBB.B5 and S. thermophilus allowed the continuous maintenance, passage and production of the combinations as co-cultures for more than 40 years now. The resulting starter cultures were used to produce Bulgarian yoghurt on industrial scale with its traditional taste, aroma and microbiological properties. Sequencing the genome of strain LBB.B5 will provide valuable data that can be used to elucidate the genetic background behind the contribution of this strain to the formation of the typical taste and aroma of Bulgarian yoghurt and its exceptional protocooperation with S. thermophilus.

Lactobacillus fermentum is a heterofermentative lactic acid bacterium (LAB) belonging to the Lactobacillaceae family within the Bacilli class of the Firmicutes phylum. The species is listed in the qualified presumption of safety (QPS) published by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) (3) and a previously described strain belonging to this species has been generally recognized as safe by the U.S Food and Drug Administration (GRAS notice n?531). L. fermentum strains have been previously reported for their different properties, including technological or probiotic functionalities. Lactobacillus fermentum NCC 2970 originates from the Nestl? Culture Collection and has also been deposited at the National Collection of Microorganisms Cultures (CNCM) under CNCM I-5068.

Lactobacillus fermentum (NCDC 400) is a common commensal organism of gastrointestinal tract (GIT) and comprehensive studied for its probiotic attributes. It is a facultative heterofermentative category of bacterium which is very much industrially important for the food and dairy based industries and particularly used as a starter culture for milk fermentation. The capability to endure the harsh environment of the gastrointestinal tract, in the presence of bile in gastric juice, is one of the uniqueness is bacterium to transiently inhabit the host. In the present study, we have used paired-end sequencing library using QIAseq FX DNA Library kit and identified total of 17733506 High Quality reads on Illumina Platform. These Reads were assembled into assembly of Lactobacillus fermentum strain NCDC 400. The identified protein coding genes were predicted using GeneMarkS wherein 1996 genes (and proteins) were found and these proteins were annotated using BlastP against NR database of NCBI with evalue < 1e-6 and 1961 of these genes were found to be homologous to Lactobacillus fermentum spp proteins in NR database.

The complete genome sequences of several pairs of closely related prokaryotes are now available. Surprisingly, even strains of the same species can differ by as much as 20 % in gene content. Several analyses of very closely related genomes comparisons reported over the last years show that there may be as much to learn about diversity. Extensive genomic comparisons are possible not only between representatives of distant evolutionary phyla, but also between species of the same phylogenetic branch where individual evolutionary events can be more readily identified. They also indicate that sequencing of one representative genome give us nowhere near a complete picture of the genetic repertoire of any species, and that new and comparative methods will be required. Remarkable innovation in sequencing technologies has been achieved making them high-throughput, faster and more cost effective. The sequencing field has experienced a major shift by the introduction of innovation sequencing technologies capable of generating sequence data at a fraction of the cost and much quicker when compared to the Sanger method. Bacteria are characterized by extensive intraspecies variation. There is not only the sequence variation found in all species, but also the presence or absence of whole genes or clusters of genes. We propose to apply the sequencing technology developed by Illumina on several strains of Lactobacillus acidophilus and helveticus to enable a comparative study that will link genotype and phenotype at the genomic level.

Isolation Comments: isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B
Comments: The research in the frame of Croatian Science Foundation project entitled „Probiotics and starter cultures – surface proteins and bacteriocins“ is aimed to deliver new generation of probiotics and functional starter cultures, thoughtfully characterised and with specific features such as production of functional surface (S)-layer proteins and bacteriocins with broad spectrum of activity towards potential food contaminants and pathogens. Among more than 200 different LAB strains isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B. Importance of S-layer proteins lies in increasing scientific evidences that some probiotic properties of lactic acid bacteria (LAB), such as enhanced survival in rigorous conditions in gastrointestinal tract and during the process of freeze-drying, adhesion to intestinal epithelial cells or inhibition of pathogens, are related to the occurrence of those proteins. Hence, it is believed that the production of S-layer proteins might be a selective criterion indicating probiotic effect of Lactobacillus species that express those specific surface proteins. Another feature specific to certain strains of LAB, which gives them a selective advantage when applied as probiotic or starter cultures, is the production of bacteriocins. Among all the isolated autochthonous LAB, three Lactobaillus plantarum strains, M92C, SF15C and D13, showed advanced bacteriocinogenic potential. Besides their application as probiotics, these strains could be considered as starter cultures with potential to improve the functionality and quality of various fermented products, while in the same time preserving their traditional sensory characteristics.

We employed gnotobiotic mice to systematically examine the importance of colonization history in shaping the gut microbiota. This study has established that colonization history has a measurable effect on assembly of the gut microbiota, a discovery that has broad implications for our understanding of the causes of spatial patterns of host-associated microbial communities and the development of strategies to modulate gut ecosystems to counteract aberrant patterns of colonization.

Comments: Challenges in cultivating microorganisms have limited the phylogenetic diversity of currently available microbial genomes. This is being addressed by advances in sequencing throughput and computational techniques that allow for the cultivation-independent recovery of high-quality bacterial and archaeal genomes directly from metagenomic data. In this study, we recovered 7,903 uncultivated genomes from >1,000 metagenomes available from the Sequence Read Archive. These genomes increase the phylogenetic diversity of current archaeal and bacterial genome trees by >30%.

Isolation Comments: isolated from fermented milk product, thereby of animal origin, whereas strains NRIC1917 and NRIC1981 were isolated from sugarcane wine and compost, respectively, thereby of vegetable origin
Comments: I order to study the mechanism underlying bile resistance of lactic acid bacteria, three strains of Lactobacillus paracasei were chosen. Strain NRIC0644 was originally isolated from fermented milk product, thereby of animal origin, whereas strains NRIC1917 and NRIC1981 were isolated from sugarcane wine and compost, respectively, thereby of vegetable origin. Preliminary test indicated vegetable-originated strains NRIC1917 and NRIC1981 were more resistant to cholate, the major component of bile compared to NRIC0644. The aim of the whole genome sequencing of these three strains was to elucidate the cause from which the difference in the bile resistance was brought about among these strains, and to find out common genetic feature for the bile resistant character. The information might be relevant for screening bile resistant lactic acid bacteria, which would contribute to develop useful probiotics.

Lactobacillus paracasei is a member of the lactic acid group of bacteria. It is a gram-positive, facultatively heterofermentative, non-spore forming microorganism and is commercially used extensively as probiotics and in the fermentation of dairy products and meat. The aim of this study is to sequence the complete genome of L. paracasei strain IIA, to determine its phylogeny and to compare and contrast its genome with other Lactobacilli.

Isolation Comments: isolated during a large scale screen to identify lactic acid bacterial strains with antifungal activitites
Comments: Lactobacillus plantarum 16 was isolated during a large scale screen to identify lactic acid bacterial strains with antifungal activitites. It was shown to have broad-spectrum antifungal activities towards a variety of food-spoilage fungi and has been successfully used as a biopreservative in a number of food models to extend product shelf life. The genome sequence of Lb. plantarum 16 can be used as a basis to discern the machinery involved in antifungal production.

Isolation Comments: isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B
Comments: The research in the frame of Croatian Science Foundation project entitled „Probiotics and starter cultures – surface proteins and bacteriocins“ is aimed to deliver new generation of probiotics and functional starter cultures, thoughtfully characterised and with specific features such as production of functional surface (S)-layer proteins and bacteriocins with broad spectrum of activity towards potential food contaminants and pathogens. Among more than 200 different LAB strains isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B. Importance of S-layer proteins lies in increasing scientific evidences that some probiotic properties of lactic acid bacteria (LAB), such as enhanced survival in rigorous conditions in gastrointestinal tract and during the process of freeze-drying, adhesion to intestinal epithelial cells or inhibition of pathogens, are related to the occurrence of those proteins. Hence, it is believed that the production of S-layer proteins might be a selective criterion indicating probiotic effect of Lactobacillus species that express those specific surface proteins. Another feature specific to certain strains of LAB, which gives them a selective advantage when applied as probiotic or starter cultures, is the production of bacteriocins. Among all the isolated autochthonous LAB, three Lactobaillus plantarum strains, M92C, SF15C and D13, showed advanced bacteriocinogenic potential. Besides their application as probiotics, these strains could be considered as starter cultures with potential to improve the functionality and quality of various fermented products, while in the same time preserving their traditional sensory characteristics.

Genome Name: Lactobacillus plantarum strain L. plantarum A6
Comments: The objective of this work was to investigate the nutritional potential of L. plantarum A6 in a food matrix using next generation sequencing . For this purpose, we first sequenced characterize the genome of this strain, in order to have the most complete overview of as possible of thits potential. Then, we compared the its transcriptome of the strain L. plantarum A6when grown in a food matrix made from pearl millet to its transcriptome when the strain is cultivated into culture medium using next generation sequencing. Genomic comparison with the strains L. plantarum WCFS1, ST-III, JDM1 and ATCC14917 allowed the identification of 362 coding sequences specific to L. plantarum A6. Furthermore, Ggenes coding important functions important for nutritional quality of the food have also been identified:, such as those involved in metabolism of polyphenols , have been identified. Some complete biosynthetic biosynthesis pathways such asof folate among others.and their expression has been characterized. In addition, Cconsidering its interest as efficiency as an amylolytic bacteriastrain, we investigated all genes involved in carbohydrate metabolism, giving special attention to starch metabolism. An extracellular alpha amylase, a neopullulanase and the maltodextrin transporters are were identified and were all highly expressed in food matrix.The combination of genomic and transcriptomic not only revealed undocumented nutritional properties of L. plantarum A6, but also documented the behaviour of this bacteria in food.

Three Lactobacillus plantarum probiotic strains (Lp790, Lp813, and Lp998) of dairy origin showed the best probiotic potential (Zago et al., 2011) and were then studied in more detail in this study. The genome sequence of this three strains was determined using a Miseq Illumina system. Genome analysis of Lp790, Lp813, and Lp998 and comparative genomics provided insight into genes and gene cassettes involved in probiotic functions, including life-style adaptation, genome synteny. Genomic chracteristics were compared to in-vivo results, in which the immunomodulation properties using models to predict for in vivo efficacy, the capacity to produce B-group vitamins and to induce cytokine production by dendritic cells were tested to characterize probiotic potential of these strains.

Challenges in cultivating microorganisms have limited the phylogenetic diversity of currently available microbial genomes. This is being addressed by advances in sequencing throughput and computational techniques that allow for the cultivation-independent recovery of high-quality bacterial and archaeal genomes directly from metagenomic data. In this study, we recovered 7,903 uncultivated genomes from >1,000 metagenomes available from the Sequence Read Archive. These genomes increase the phylogenetic diversity of current archaeal and bacterial genome trees by >30%.

A necessary step in the understanding a function of gut microbiota is to obtain gut anaerobes in pure cultures, sequence them completely, predict their characteristic features and use them in all downstream experiments. In this study we therefore cultured and sequenced isolates from chicken caecum among which we identified isolates belonging to 6 different phyla including Firmicutes, Bacteroidetes, Actinobacteria, Proteobacteria, Verrucomicrobia, Elusimicrobia and Synergistetes.

Gnotobiotic mice colonized with known bacterial communities are extensively used as models to study the role of the gut microbiota and its association with diseases. We developed a defined consortium of 12 cultivable murine isolates, named the Oligo-Mouse Microbiota (Oligo-MM), which represent the main bacterial phyla colonizing the mouse and human intestine. Such a defined bacterial collection represents an ideal model for analyzing genome evolution of bacteria in their natural host, and for predicting their functionome and metabolic capacity, both as whole community and as single species.

Challenges in cultivating microorganisms have limited the phylogenetic diversity of currently available microbial genomes. This is being addressed by advances in sequencing throughput and computational techniques that allow for the cultivation-independent recovery of high-quality bacterial and archaeal genomes directly from metagenomic data. In this study, we recovered 7,903 uncultivated genomes from >1,000 metagenomes available from the Sequence Read Archive. These genomes increase the phylogenetic diversity of current archaeal and bacterial genome trees by >30%.

Several lactic acid bacteria, including Lactobacillus reuteri, are associated with reduction of Type 1 Diabetes symptoms in rodent studies. However, BioBreeding diabetes prone (BB-DP) rats treated with L. reuteri strain TD1 are reported to exhibit similar, if not greater, incidence of Type 1 Diabetes when compared to untreated rats.

Isolation Source: 396 human stool samples we identified 7,381 such MetaGenomic Species
Isolation Comments: derived from 396 human stool samples we identified 7,381 such MetaGenomic Species
Comments: Metagenomic data acquired by deep sequencing is immensely complex, lacks apparent structure and is typically dominated by unknown species. Using an abundance co-variance strategy, we group highly co-varying genes into MetaGenomic Species, which represent a wide range of biological entities: bacterial genomes, plasmids, genomic islands, clonal variation and bacteriophages. Applying this concept to a new 3.9 million microbial gene catalogue derived from 396 human stool samples we identified 7,381 such MetaGenomic Species. They range in size from 3 to 6,319 genes, with 741 MetaGenomic Species resembling bacterial genomes in number of genes contained. The Meta-Genomic Species displays remarkable consistency in taxonomy and GC content. 247 of the MetaGenomic Species assemblies even pass the HMP high quality draft genome criteria. A large proportion (73%) of the MetaGenomic Species displays no sequence similarity to any previously sequenced organism. Smaller MetaGenomic Species are enriched for genes characteristic for bacteriophages and functions important for biotic interactions and show strong dependencies to gene-rich MetaGenomic Species. We present the first unsupervised structuring of a highly complex series of metagenomic samples into biological entities, including a global analysis of the genetic interdependencies between bacteria, plasmids, phages and genetic islands in the human distal gut.

Challenges in cultivating microorganisms have limited the phylogenetic diversity of currently available microbial genomes. This is being addressed by advances in sequencing throughput and computational techniques that allow for the cultivation-independent recovery of high-quality bacterial and archaeal genomes directly from metagenomic data. These genomes increase the phylogenetic diversity of current archaeal and bacterial genome trees by >30%.

Isolation Comments: isolated from fecal samples after being enriched with the respective prebiotic
Comments: One strategy for enhancing establishment of probiotic bacteria in the human intestinal tract is the parallel administration of a prebiotic, which is referred to as a synbiotic. With this project we present a novel method for the selection of probiotic strains to be used in synbiotic applications, In Vivo Selection (IVS). Candidate strains are isolated from fecal samples after being enriched with the respective prebiotic. To test the potential of IVS, we isolated bifidobacteria by selective culture from human subjects after galactooligosaccharides (GOS) consumption . A retrospective analysis of the fecal microbiota of one of the subjects revealed that one strain, Bifidobacterium adolescentis IVS-1, was enriched 8-fold. The functionality of IVS-1 and GOS as a synergistic synbiotic was then tested in rats that received either the bacterial strain alone, the prebiotic alone, the synbiotic combination, or no supplement.

Gnotobiotic mice colonized with known bacterial communities are extensively used as models to study the role of the gut microbiota and its association with diseases. We developed a defined consortium of 12 cultivable murine isolates, named the Oligo-Mouse Microbiota (Oligo-MM), which represent the main bacterial phyla colonizing the mouse and human intestine. Such a defined bacterial collection represents an ideal model for analyzing genome evolution of bacteria in their natural host, and for predicting their functionome and metabolic capacity, both as whole community and as single species.

Isolation Comments: isolated from the mammalian GIT, and some from the vaginal and oral cavity
Comments: Bifidobacterium. Representatives of this genus naturally colonize the human gastrointestinal tract (GIT) and are important for establishing and maintaining homeostasis of the intestinal ecosystem to allow for normal digestion. Their presence has been associated with beneficial health effects, such as prevention of diarrhea, amelioration of lactose intolerance, or immunomodulation. The stabilizing effect on GIT microflora is attributed to the capacity of bifidobacteria to produce bacteriocins, which are bacteriostatic agents with a broad spectrum of action, and to their pH-reducing activity. Most of the ~30 known species of bifidobacteria have been isolated from the mammalian GIT, and some from the vaginal and oral cavity. All are obligate anaerobes belonging to the Actinomycetales, branch of Gram-positive bacteria with high GC content that also includes Corynebacteria, Mycobacteria, and Streptomycetes.Bifidobacterium bifidum. Bifidobacterium bifidum is commonly isolated from human feces and is used a a probiotic to maintain healthy gut flora.Bifidobacterium bifidum DSM 20456.  Bifidobacterium bifidum DSM 20456 (ATCC 27723) was isolated from the feces of a breast-fed infant and is a member of normal human gut microbial community. This strain is the type strain and is part of a comprehensive, sequence-based survey of members of the normal human gut microbiota of children and adults. A joint effort of the WU-GSC and the Center for Genome Sciences at Washington University School of Medicine, the purpose of this survey is to provide the general scientific community with a broad view of the gene content of 100 representatives of the major divisions represented in the intestine's microbial community. This information should provide a frame of reference for analyzing metagenomic studies of the human gut microbiome.

The Meta-Genomic Species displays remarkable consistency in taxonomy and GC content. 247 of the MetaGenomic Species assemblies even pass the HMP high quality draft genome criteria. A large proportion (73%) of the MetaGenomic Species displays no sequence similarity to any previously sequenced organism. Smaller MetaGenomic Species are enriched for genes characteristic for bacteriophages and functions important for biotic interactions and show strong dependencies to gene-rich MetaGenomic Species. We present the first unsupervised structuring of a highly complex series of metagenomic samples into biological entities, including a global analysis of the genetic interdependencies between bacteria, plasmids, phages and genetic islands in the human distal gut.

Comments: Eczema is common chronic inflammatory skin disorder with significant impact on child health, and its prevalence is increasing worldwide. It is known that the interaction between gut microbes and the host immune system influences early life development of the immune system. We and others have shown that the composition of the stool microbiota signatures differ between eczema and healthy controls in infancy. The scope of work will include the identification of functional and structural gene composition present in the stools of infants with and without eczema by comparative metagenomics. The proposed study will provide the initial steps towards a comprehensive evaluation of the bacterial gene composition in stool microbiota in relation to development of eczema.

Isolation Comments: isolated bacteria
Comments: Recently, bacterial communities (microbiota) have been discovered in the female bladder. Thus, the “sterile urine” paradigm is no longer valid. In an effort to provide a comprehensive view of the newly discovered female urinary microbiota (FUM), we have established an Enhanced Quantitative Urine Culture (EQUC) protocol. EQUC isolates bacteria from 75-90% of urine samples deemed ‘no growth’ by the standard clinical microbiology urine culture method. We have begun to sequence and annotate the genomes of these isolated bacteria.

Comments: Bifidobacterium breve UCC2003 . This strain (NCIMB 8807; UCC2003) was originally isolated from an infant nursing stool. This organism will used for comparative genomics with other Bifidobacterium species.

Bifidobacteria are naturally found in the human large intestine and are used as probiotic bacteria due to their beneficial effects on human health. Bifidobacteria are known for difficulties in gene manipulation, especially in the generation of gene knockout mutants. Bifidobacterium longum 105-A shows high transformation efficiency and allows for gene knockout mutant generation through homologous recombination. Here, we report the complete genome sequence of the strain 105-A.

Isolation Comments: derived from 396 human stool samples we identified 7,381 such MetaGenomic Species
Comments: Metagenomic data acquired by deep sequencing is immensely complex, lacks apparent structure and is typically dominated by unknown species. Using an abundance co-variance strategy, we group highly co-varying genes into MetaGenomic Species, which represent a wide range of biological entities: bacterial genomes, plasmids, genomic islands, clonal variation and bacteriophages. Applying this concept to a new 3.9 million microbial gene catalogue derived from 396 human stool samples we identified 7,381 such MetaGenomic Species. They range in size from 3 to 6,319 genes, with 741 MetaGenomic Species resembling bacterial genomes in number of genes contained. The Meta-Genomic Species displays remarkable consistency in taxonomy and GC content. 247 of the MetaGenomic Species assemblies even pass the HMP high quality draft genome criteria. A large proportion (73%) of the MetaGenomic Species displays no sequence similarity to any previously sequenced organism. Smaller MetaGenomic Species are enriched for genes characteristic for bacteriophages and functions important for biotic interactions and show strong dependencies to gene-rich MetaGenomic Species. We present the first unsupervised structuring of a highly complex series of metagenomic samples into biological entities, including a global analysis of the genetic interdependencies between bacteria, plasmids, phages and genetic islands in the human distal gut.

Isolation Comments: isolated from the gastrointestinal tract of a healthy adult Indian
Comments: Bifidobacterium longum, a Gram-positive anaerobic rod-shaped bacterium, present in the infant and adult gastrointestinal tracts and contributes significantly in oligosaccharide metabolism and biosynthesis of vitamins, amino acids, short chain fatty acids, bacteriocins and linoleic acid. Several strains of B. longum are well known as probiotic bacteria and used in combination with traditional therapies to treat inflammatory bowl disease (IBD) and other health disorders. In the present study, we report the whole genome sequence of B. longum isolated from the gastrointestinal tract of a healthy adult Indian.

Challenges in cultivating microorganisms have limited the phylogenetic diversity of currently available microbial genomes. This is being addressed by advances in sequencing throughput and computational techniques that allow for the cultivation-independent recovery of high-quality bacterial and archaeal genomes directly from metagenomic data. In this study, we recovered 7,903 uncultivated genomes from >1,000 metagenomes available from the Sequence Read Archive. These genomes increase the phylogenetic diversity of current archaeal and bacterial genome trees by >30%.

Isolation Comments: isolated bacteria
Comments: Recently, bacterial communities (microbiota) have been discovered in the female bladder. Thus, the “sterile urine” paradigm is no longer valid. In an effort to provide a comprehensive view of the newly discovered female urinary microbiota (FUM), we have established an Enhanced Quantitative Urine Culture (EQUC) protocol. EQUC isolates bacteria from 75-90% of urine samples deemed ‘no growth’ by the standard clinical microbiology urine culture method. We have begun to sequence and annotate the genomes of these isolated bacteria.

Isolation Comments: isolated directly from probiotics capsules
Comments: Administration of probiotics to premature newborns prevents necrotizing enterocolitis and reduces all cause mortality. Two cases of Bifidobacterium infantis bacteremia were diagnosed in newborns receiving probiotics. This study describes the sequence of the two strains causing bacteremia retrieved by blood culture and six other strains isolated directly from probiotics capsules. DNA was sequenced on an Illumina MiSeq system with a 2x150 bp run. SNP analysis was performed to confirm the probiotic origin of the B. infantis strain recovered from neonates with bacteremia.

Isolation Comments: isolated from the feces of healthy children and identified as Bifidobacterium longum subsp
Comments: A complete genome sequence of a bifidobacterium longum subsp. longum CMCC P0001. The bacterium strain was originally isolated from the feces of healthy children and identified as Bifidobacterium longum subsp. longum by National Institute for the Control of Pharmaceutical and Biological Products (NICPBP), China. The strain was initially deposited in China Center for Type Culture Collection (CCTCC) with registration number M98003 and it was designated as standard strain for probiotics production by China Medical Culture Collection Center (CMCC) with assigned number CMCC P0001 in 2011.

Comments: Bifidobacteria are an important component of the human intestinal microbiota. The objective is to obtain the complete genome sequence and annotation of strain B. longum subsp. longum GT15, isolated in 2011 from the gastrointestinal tract (GIT) of a healthy adult from Central region of Russia. The complete genome sequence of this strain, will be used as pharmaceutical product, because a lot of probiotic genes were found in this strain. This is the first strain isolated from the microbiota of the Russian human.
